o really understand her reasoning. Have her help me look at other school options (public/private). Weigh pros and cons with her. See if she feels that there is something I could do differently that would satisfy her needs (does she need new friends? does she feel she is falling behind? is she just not enjoying school or is my relationship with her as her teacher conflicting with my role as her mother?). But ultimately, I would have no issue allowing her to try it for a time to see if it works for her, and if it did, I would have no issue keeping her in a traditional school setting. I'm not anti-trad school at all. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="925" language="en" documentId="559" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="snugsmama" date="09/05/2013" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://community.babycenter.com/post/a44369503/home_schooling_debate_this_hypothetical?cpg=21" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="559" notes="" title="Home schooling: Debate this hypothetical"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="256"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="257" end="925"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43"/></xmi:XMI>